Formation:

  • Union of ventral rami of C5, 6, 7, 8 and T1
  • Sympathetic fibres communicates with rami
  • Prefixed
    • Large C4
    • Small T1
  • Postfixed

Exit of roots - Pass between scalenus anterior and scalenus medius

Derive a part of prevertebral fascia that continues around the brachial plexus and axillary vessels as - Cervicoaxillary canal

Watch the video

Components

  • Roots
    • ventral rami of C5, 6, 7, 8 and T1
  • Trunks
    • C5 and C6 unite to form upper trunk
    • C7 continues as middle trunk
    • C8 and T1 unite to form lower trunk
  • Divisions
    • Each trunk divides into anterior and posterior divisions
    • Posterior divisions supply extensors
  • Cords
    • Anterior divisions of upper and middle trunks unite to form lateral cord
    • Anterior division of lower trunk continues as medial cord
    • Posterior divisions of all trunks unite to form posterior cord

Cords are named after their relations to second part of axillary artery

Approaches to brachial plexus block

  • Interscalene approach
    • The needle is inserted 3-4 cm above the clavicle and advanced at an angle almost perpendicular to the skin plane in between scalenus anterior and scalenus medius
  • Supraclavicular approach
    • The needle is inserted first in an anteroposterior direction 2.5 cm lateral to the clavicular insertion of sternocleidomastoid, almost perpendicularly to the skin
  • Axillary approach
    • The needle is inserted through the axilla â€“ after identifying the axillary artery pulsations

Brachial plexus injury

  • Motorcycle accidents are the most common cause
  • Other etiologies are
  • Birth injuries
  • Missile + stab wounds
  • Traction applied to plexus
